      "In visual design, what is 'White Space' (Negative Space)?": "The empty space between and around elements that gives the design 'room to breathe'.",
      "Why is White Space important in UI design?": "It improves readability, reduces cognitive overload, and clarifies relationships between elements.",
      "What is Visual Hierarchy?": "Arranging elements in order of importance, guiding the user's eye from most critical to least critical.",
      "Which characteristic is the strongest tool for establishing Visual Hierarchy?": "Size (making the most important thing the largest).",
      "How do western users typically scan a text-heavy webpage?": "In an F-Pattern (across the top, down the side, across the middle).",
      "How do users typically scan highly visual, image-based websites?": "In a Z-Pattern (left-to-right, diagonal down-left, left-to-right).",
      "In color psychology, what emotion or action is most commonly associated with the color Red?": "Excitement, urgency, or an error/warning.",
      "In color psychology, what is the color Blue often used to convey?": "Trust, security, and professionalism (often used by banks).",
      "What is the 60-30-10 Rule in UI color design?": "A formula for dividing your palette: 60% dominant base color, 30% secondary color, and 10% accent color (like for buttons).",
      "What is an 'Affordance' in UX design?": "A visual clue that tells the user how an object should be used (e.g., a button looking clickable).",
      "Why is 'Consistency' a golden rule in UI design?": "It reduces the user's learning curve because things behave exactly as they expect across the whole site.",
      "What does the Gestalt Principle of 'Proximity' state?": "Elements that are placed close to each other are perceived as being related or part of a group.",
      "What does the Gestalt Principle of 'Similarity' state?": "Elements that look similar (in shape, color, or size) are perceived as having the same function.",
      "What is 'Cognitive Load' in UX?": "The amount of mental effort required by the user to understand and navigate an interface.",
      "A great UX designer aims to ____________ cognitive load.": "Reduce",
      "What is the primary purpose of a 'Call to Action' (CTA)?": "To prompt the user to take a specific, desired action (like 'Buy Now' or 'Sign Up').",
      "Which of the following is a characteristic of a good Call to Action (CTA)?": "It stands out visually using a strong accent color and clear, action-oriented text.",
      "What is a 'Wireframe'?": "A low-fidelity, structural blueprint showing the layout of elements without distracting design details.",
      "What is a 'Prototype' in UI/UX?": "An interactive model of the design that simulates how the final product will feel and function before coding begins.",
      "Why is it cheaper to fix a usability problem during the Wireframing/Prototyping phase rather than after the site is coded?": "Because changing lines on a blueprint takes minutes, while rewriting complex code architecture can take weeks.",
      "What is A/B Testing?": "Showing two slightly different versions of a design to users to see which one performs better.",
      "What is the 'Three-Click Rule' in UX?": "A theory that users will leave a site if they can't find what they want within three clicks.",
      "In typography, what is 'Tracking'?": "The uniform spacing between all letters in a block of text.",
      "In typography, what is 'Leading' (Line-Height)?": "The vertical space between lines of text, crucial for readability.",
      "Which font type is generally considered best for large blocks of text on digital screens because of its clean edges?": "Sans-Serif",
      "What is 'Friction' in User Experience?": "Anything that slows down, confuses, or prevents a user from completing their goal.",
      "Requiring a user to fill out a 20-field form just to download a free PDF is an example of:": "High Friction.",
      "What is a 'Dark Pattern' in UI design?": "A deceptive interface trick designed to manipulate users into doing things they didn't intend to do (like a hidden subscription fee).",
      "Which of the following is a classic example of a Dark Pattern?": "A tiny, barely visible 'unsubscribe' link hidden at the bottom of a spam email.",
      "What is the 'Fold' in web design?": "The imaginary line where the bottom of the user's screen cuts off the page before they scroll.",
      "Why is 'Above the Fold' critical real estate?": "Because it is the first thing users see without scrolling, making it the best place for your core message and CTA.",
      "What is 'Responsive Design' primarily concerned with?": "Ensuring the UI adapts gracefully to provide a good UX on any device (mobile, tablet, desktop).",
      "What does the 'Accessibility' (a11y) aspect of UX focus on?": "Ensuring the site is usable by people of all abilities and disabilities.",
      "Adequate color contrast is a critical rule for both UI aesthetics and:": "Accessibility for visually impaired users.",
      "What is a 'User Persona'?": "A fictional character created to represent a specific user type, helping designers empathize with their target audience.",
      "When designing for a 'User Persona', what is the most important question to ask?": "'What problem is this specific user trying to solve?'",
      "What is 'Microcopy'?": "The tiny bits of text on an interface (like button labels, error messages, and tooltips) that guide the user.",
      "Changing a button label from 'Submit' to 'Get Your Free Guide' is an improvement in:": "Microcopy and UX.",
      "What is 'Feedback' in UI design?": "The system acknowledging a user's action (e.g., a button changing color when clicked, or a success message appearing).",
      "If a user clicks a 'Buy' button and nothing visually happens for 5 seconds while it loads, what UX principle has failed?": "System Feedback",
      "What is 'Breadcrumb Navigation'?": "A secondary navigation scheme that shows the user's location in a site's hierarchy (e.g., Home > Electronics > TVs).",
      "What is the 'Law of Proximity' a subset of?": "Gestalt Psychology.",
      "Why should you never use color as the *only* way to convey important information?": "Because colorblind users might not be able to perceive the difference.",
      "What is 'Card Sorting'?": "A UX research method where users organize topics into groups, helping designers build logical navigation menus.",
      "Which tool is commonly used by professionals to create high-fidelity UI prototypes?": "Figma",
      "The phrase 'Don't Make Me Think' is a famous UX mantra. What does it mean?": "Interfaces should be obvious, self-explanatory, and intuitive so users don't have to figure out how to use them.",
      "What is 'Accessibility Contrast Ratio'?": "The mathematical difference in brightness between text and its background color.",
      "If a website's primary goal is a calm, relaxing meditation app, which color palette is the most appropriate UI choice?": "Soft Blues, Greens, and Whites.",

      // CHAPTER 7: The Bones
      "Why is a code editor like Visual Studio Code better than a basic text editor like Notepad?": "It color-codes your code and checks for mistakes as you type.",
      "Which tool acts like a 'spell-checker' for your HTML code to find tricky errors?": "The W3C validation website",
      "What is the primary goal of 'responsive design'?": "To ensure the website looks great and functions well on any screen size, including mobile phones.",
      "What is the very first line of code required in a modern HTML5 document (the document type declaration)?": "<!DOCTYPE html>",
      "In the HTML 'family tree', which element is considered the root that holds everything else together?": "<html>",
      "Why is it important to include the `lang='en'` attribute in the root html tag?": "It tells search engines and screen readers what language the page is in.",
      "Which part of the HTML boilerplate holds important information that the user does NOT see on the page?": "<head>",
      "What does the `<meta charset='UTF-8'>` tag do?": "It tells the browser to use a standard character set that supports almost all symbols.",
      "Which invisible tag provides a short summary of your page for search engine results like Google?": "<meta name='description'>",
      "Which section of the HTML document holds all the content the user actually sees (text, images, video)?": "<body>",
      "All web servers look for a specific file name to serve as a website's default home page. What is it?": "index.html",
      "What is an 'empty element' in HTML?": "A tag that has no content inside it and only needs one tag (like <br>).",
      "What does the 'First-In, Last-Out' rule refer to?": "When nesting tags, the last tag you open is the first one you must close.",
      "Using the suitcase analogy, what happens if you try to close an outer tag before closing the inner nested tag?": "It results in incorrect nesting (overlapping tags) and can break the layout.",
      "Which tag is used to create a standard paragraph of text?": "<p>",
      "Which tag is used to logically emphasize text, usually rendering it in italics?": "<em>",
      "What is an HTML 'Attribute'?": "Special instructions added to the starting tag to give elements extra information (like class='intro').",
      "Why should developers use Semantic Tags (like <article> or <footer>) instead of generic <div> tags?": "Their names describe exactly what kind of content they contain, which is great for SEO and screen readers.",
      "What is the primary purpose of a creating a wireframe before coding?": "To map out the logical structure and placement of semantic areas before getting distracted by design.",
      "Which semantic tag marks the introduction of a section or page?": "<header>",
      "Which semantic tag is used to wrap a list of hypertext navigation links?": "<nav>",
      "Which semantic tag marks a self-contained piece of content, like a blog post or news story?": "<article>",
      "What is the difference between a block-level element and an inline element?": "Block elements take up the full width and stack; inline elements sit next to each other and don't start a new line.",
      "Which element represents a generic container used to group elements when no semantic tag fits?": "<div>",
      "Which text-level element indicates content of strong importance (usually rendered bold)?": "<strong>",
      "Which tag is used to create a numbered, sequential list?": "<ol>",
      "In a Description List (<dl>), what tag is used for the term being defined?": "<dt>",
      "Which attribute is REQUIRED in an <img> tag to provide a description for screen readers?": "alt",
      "Which attribute in an <img> tag tells the browser exactly where to find the image file?": "src",
      "What tag is used to create a clickable hypertext link?": "<a>",
      "In a link, what does the attribute `target='_blank'` do?": "Opens the link in a new browser tab.",
      "What is the difference between an Absolute Path and a Relative Path?": "Absolute paths are the full URL (https://...); relative paths are the path from the current file to the target file.",
      "Why do we use character entity references like `&copy;`?": "To display symbols not found on a standard keyboard, like the copyright symbol.",
      "What tag is specifically designed to hold a long quote from another source and visually indents it?": "blockquote",
      "In order to connect an external CSS file to an HTML document, which tag must be placed inside the <head>?": "<link rel='stylesheet' href='...'>",
      "What does the `href` attribute stand for in an anchor tag?": "Hypertext Reference",
      "Which tag should be used to wrap the name of the author or the title of a work being quoted?": "<cite>",
      "If you want a link to open the user's default email program, what prefix do you use in the href?": "mailto:",
      "If you want a link to allow mobile users to tap to call a phone number, what prefix do you use in the href?": "tel:",
      "Which HTML tag acts as a generic inline container for styling small runs of text without starting a new line?": "<span>",
      "What is the correct syntax to add a class named 'active' to a paragraph?": "<p class='active'>",
      "Which tag is used to mark a thematic break in content, usually displaying as a horizontal line?": "<hr>",
      "Which grouping element is best used to mark content that shares a common theme or purpose on the page?": "<section>",
      "Which grouping element marks content that is related to the main article but usually placed to the side?": "<aside>",
      "In an unordered list (<ul>), what tag must wrap every individual bullet point?": "<li>",
      "If an HTML document does not have a <title> tag, what will the browser display in the tab?": "The filename (e.g., index.html)",
      "Why is the `<meta name='viewport'>` tag considered mandatory for modern websites?": "It tells mobile devices to render the page at its actual width rather than zooming out to show a desktop version.",
      "What happens if you use a relative path like `href='about.html'` but the file is actually inside a folder named 'pages'?": "The link will break and show a 'File Not Found' error.",
      "What is the purpose of the <figcaption> tag?": "To provide a caption specifically associated with a <figure> element.",
      "If you want to display the exact code `<p>` on a webpage without the browser interpreting it as a paragraph, what entity must you use for the less-than sign?": "&lt;",
      "Which tag is used to mark text that represents computer code?": "<code>",
      "In the curriculum persona, what was 'Organizer Olivia' primarily looking for?": "A clear, logically structured page to easily find location and contact info.",

      // CHAPTER 8: The Clothes
      "What is the primary function of Browser Developer Tools?": "To see which CSS rules are affecting an element and test changes live without altering your files.",
      "In the CSS hierarchy of power, which type of style has the ultimate 'final say' (highest priority)?": "Inline Styles",
      "What is an External Stylesheet?": "A separate .css file linked in the <head> of the document.",
      "If an element has a red color set in an External stylesheet but a blue color set Inline, what color will it be?": "Blue, because Inline styles have the highest priority.",
      "What is the purpose of vendor prefixes like `-webkit-` or `-moz-`?": "They were used by browsers to test new, experimental CSS features before they became standard.",
      "What does the 'C' in CSS stand for, and what does it mean?": "Cascading: the order of rules matters, and the last rule read by the browser wins ties.",
      "If you set `font-family: Arial;` on the `<body>` tag, why do all the paragraphs inside it also become Arial?": "Because of Style Inheritance.",
      "What is the format of a Hexadecimal color code?": "A hash (#) followed by six digits (0-9 and A-F).",
      "What do the three numbers in an RGB color code represent?": "Red, Green, Blue intensity from 0 to 255.",
      "Why might a web designer choose HSL over Hex codes?": "HSL is easier for humans to understand and tweak (Hue, Saturation, Lightness).",
      "How do you make a color 50% transparent using RGBA or HSLA?": "Set the Alpha channel value to 0.5.",
      "In CSS Specificity, which selector acts as the 'heavyweight champ' (highest specificity)?": "ID Selector (#main-header)",
      "What does the descendant selector `article p` target?": "Any <p> tag that is anywhere inside an <article>.",
      "What does the child selector `article > p` target?": "Only <p> tags that are a direct child (one level deep) of an <article>.",
      "What does the wildcard selector `*` do?": "Selects every single element on the page.",
      "What is a 'font stack'?": "A list of fonts provided in CSS, starting with the first choice and ending with generic backups.",
      "What is the defining characteristic of a 'serif' font?": "It has little 'feet' or strokes at the ends of the letters.",
      "Which generic font family has letters that are all exactly the same width?": "monospace",
      "What is a 'web font'?": "A font linked from a service (like Google Fonts) that the browser downloads automatically.",
      "Why is it a best practice to use `rem` units for font sizes instead of fixed `px` (pixels)?": "rem units are relative to the root font size, allowing visually impaired users to scale up the text using browser settings.",
      "What do the Viewport Units (`vw` and `vh`) measure?": "Percentages of the visible browser window's width/height.",
      "Which CSS property is used to push the first line of a paragraph inward?": "text-indent",
      "What does the `line-height` property adjust?": "The vertical space between lines of text.",
      "If you want text to align to the right edge of its container, which property do you use?": "text-align: right;",
      "What is a CSS 'pseudo-class'?": "A keyword added to a selector that specifies a special state (like :hover).",
      "Which pseudo-class targets a link that the user has already clicked on?": ":visited",
      "Which pseudo-class targets an element the precise moment it is being clicked (mouse down)?": ":active",
      "Which pseudo-class is critical for keyboard accessibility, targeting an element when a user tabs to it?": ":focus",
      "How would you select the very last paragraph in a group of siblings?": "p:last-child",
      "What does the structural pseudo-class `:nth-child(even)` do when applied to table rows (<tr>)?": "Selects alternating rows (2, 4, 6) for 'zebra striping'.",
      "What is a 'pseudo-element' (like `::before`) used for?": "To style a specific part of an element or inject 'phantom' content without changing the HTML.",
      "Which property is REQUIRED to bring a `::before` or `::after` pseudo-element to life?": "content",
      "What is 'Progressive Enhancement'?": "Starting with a simple, solid baseline for all browsers, then layering on advanced features for modern browsers.",
      "What does a CSS Validator do?": "It checks your code for syntax errors and typos like a strict teacher.",
      "In the CSS rule `h1 { color: blue; }`, what is the 'selector'?": "h1",
      "In the CSS rule `h1 { color: blue; }`, what is the 'property'?": "color",
      "What character is used to separate the property and the value in a CSS declaration?": "Colon (:)",
      "What character MUST be placed at the very end of a CSS declaration to close it?": "Semicolon (;)",
      "If you want to style elements with the class 'highlight', what is the correct selector syntax?": ".highlight",
      "If you want to style an element with the ID 'main-nav', what is the correct selector syntax?": "#main-nav",
      "How do you group multiple selectors so they share the exact same style rule?": "Separate them with a comma (e.g., `h1, h2, h3`).",
      "What does the `text-transform: uppercase;` property do?": "Changes all letters to capital letters visually without altering the HTML.",
      "Which property changes the color of the text itself?": "color",
      "What does `font-style: italic;` do?": "Slants the text.",
      "If you want to remove the default underline from a hyperlink, which property do you use?": "text-decoration: none;",
      "What does the `opacity` property control?": "How transparent an entire element is (0.0 is invisible, 1.0 is solid).",
      "What is the purpose of the `@charset 'UTF-8';` rule at the top of a CSS file?": "It specifies the character encoding, ensuring symbols and international text render correctly.",
      "How do you write a comment inside a CSS file?": "/* Comment */",
      "In the persona profile, what does 'Science Student Sam' rely on to quickly scan articles?": "Clean typography, clear link states, and organized styling.",
      "If you write `p { color: red; }` at line 10, and `p { color: blue; }` at line 50, what color will paragraphs be? Why?": "Blue, because of the 'Cascading' rule where later styles override earlier ones.",
      "Which of these is NOT a valid way to write the color white in CSS?": "hsl(0, 0%, 0%)",
      "If you want to target an input field only when it has the attribute `type='text'`, what selector do you use?": "input[type='text']",

      // CHAPTER 9: The Style
      "If an element has 100px width, 10px padding, and a 5px border (using content-box), what is the total rendered width?": "130px",
      "The 'rem' unit is relative to the font size of which element?": "The root (<html>) element",
      "What is 'Margin Collapse'?": "When adjacent vertical margins combine into a single margin.",
      "Which unit represents 1% of the browser window's width?": "vw",
      "What does the 'Mobile-First' design strategy entail?": "Coding styles for small screens first, then using min-width media queries for larger screens.",
      "An element with 'position: absolute' is positioned relative to what?": "The closest non-static positioned ancestor",
      "Which CSS property controls the stacking order of overlapping elements on the Z-axis?": "z-index",
      "Which position value acts as 'relative' until it reaches a specific scroll threshold, then stays in place?": "sticky",
      "Which position value glues an element to the viewport so it never moves when the user scrolls?": "fixed",
      "In Flexbox, which property aligns items along the Cross Axis (usually vertically)?": "align-items",
      "What does 'justify-content: space-between' do in a flex container?": "Pushes the first item to the start edge and the last item to the end edge, spacing the rest evenly.",
      "If flex items run out of horizontal space, which property allows them to drop to a new line?": "flex-wrap: wrap",
      "CSS Grid is primarily designed for what kind of layouts?": "2-Dimensional (Rows and Columns simultaneously)",
      "What is the 'fr' unit in CSS Grid?": "Fractional Unit of available free space",
      "How do you create 3 equally sized columns in CSS Grid?": "grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr",
      "What does the 'gap' property do?": "Sets the space between grid tracks or flex items without using margins.",
      "Which of the following is the correct syntax for a media query targeting screens 600px wide or smaller?": "@media (max-width: 600px)",
      "What is the standard 'magic fix' to ensure images never overflow their parent containers?": "max-width: 100%",
      "Which CSS property completely removes an element from the document flow as if it doesn't exist?": "display: none",
      "To make a grid item stretch across two columns, you use:": "grid-column: span 2",
      "What is the primary benefit of using `box-sizing: border-box`?": "Padding and borders are included in the element's total width and height.",
      "What does the `vh` unit stand for?": "Viewport Height",
      "In Flexbox, what does the `flex-grow` property determine?": "How much of the available free space the item should take up.",
      "What is the default `flex-direction` of a newly created flex container?": "row",
      "Which CSS property defines the height of rows in a CSS Grid?": "grid-template-rows",
      "What does `grid-column: 1 / 3` signify for a grid item?": "It starts at column line 1 and ends at column line 3 (spanning 2 columns).",
      "If you use `@media (min-width: 1024px)`, the CSS rules inside will apply to:": "Screens 1024px and wider.",
      "How does `position: relative` affect an element?": "It allows you to move it using top/bottom/left/right relative to its normal position.",
      "If an element has `position: static`, what happens if you apply `top: 50px` to it?": "Nothing happens; static elements ignore top/bottom/left/right.",
      "How do you properly declare a custom CSS variable on the root pseudo-class?": ":root { --primary-color: #f00; }",
      "How do you apply a previously declared CSS variable named `--main-bg` to an element?": "background-color: var(--main-bg);",
      "If text is spilling out of its container, which property forces a scrollbar to appear inside the box?": "overflow: scroll;",
      "Which CSS function allows you to perform math directly in your stylesheet (e.g., subtracting pixels from percentages)?": "calc()",
      "What is the classic CSS technique to horizontally center a block-level element (like a container div) with a set width?": "margin: 0 auto;",
      "What makes `display: inline-block` different from `display: inline`?": "It sits inline with text but respects width and height properties.",
      "Which CSS Grid property allows you to map out your layout using named visual strings?": "grid-template-areas",
      "In Flexbox, what is the difference between `align-items` and `align-content`?": "align-items handles individual items on a single line; align-content handles the spacing of multiple wrapped lines.",
      "Which property allows you to visually re-arrange the sequence of flex items without changing the HTML markup?": "order",
      "Can a `z-index` have a negative value (e.g., `z-index: -1`)?": "Yes, pushing the element behind the default background layer.",
      "What does the `<meta name='viewport'>` tag do in the HTML head?": "It tells mobile devices not to zoom out and to render the page at its actual device width.",
      "The `em` unit is relative to:": "The font-size of its direct parent element.",
      "What happens if a block element's `width` is set to 1000px, but the user's screen is only 400px wide?": "The browser creates a horizontal scrollbar.",
      "Which CSS property maintains an element's proportions (like a 16:9 video) as it resizes?": "aspect-ratio",
      "In CSS Grid, what is the primary difference between `auto-fill` and `auto-fit`?": "auto-fill leaves empty tracks if there's extra space; auto-fit collapses empty tracks to stretch existing items.",
      "What does the `minmax()` function do in CSS Grid?": "It defines a size range for a track, setting a minimum size and allowing it to grow to a maximum size.",
      "Which CSS function is perfect for fluid typography, allowing font size to scale smoothly between a minimum and maximum value?": "clamp()",
      "If a child div is set to `width: 50%`, it will take up half the width of:": "Its direct parent element.",
      "In Flexbox, what does `justify-content: space-evenly` do?": "Ensures the gap between all items AND the edges of the container are exactly identical.",
      "How does `visibility: hidden` differ from `display: none`?": "visibility: hidden makes the element invisible but it still takes up physical space; display: none removes it from the layout entirely.",
      "Which media query detects if the user is holding their phone sideways?": "@media (orientation: landscape)",
      "If an ID selector (`#header`) and a class selector (`.hero`) both target the same element with different colors, which one wins?": "The ID selector, because IDs have higher specificity.",
      "Which pseudo-class targets an element when the user moves their mouse over it?": ":hover",

      // CHAPTER 10: Sights & Sounds
      "Which property is the 'Magic Reset' that prevents padding from expanding a box?": "box-sizing: border-box",
      "What is the primary benefit of SVG over other image formats?": "Perfectly sharp at any size (Vector)",
      "In the 8-step SSL Handshake, what is the first thing the browser does?": "Asks for a secure session",
      "Which unit is relative to the Root HTML element's font size?": "rem",
      "What is a 'Digital Footprint'?": "A permanent record of online activity",
      "Which attribute is REQUIRED for a video to autoplay in most browsers?": "muted",
      "What does PII stand for in privacy law?": "Personally Identifiable Information",
      "Which Photoshop tool is used to 'shrink' the total pixel dimensions of an image?": "Image Size",
      "What tag is used to specify multiple file formats (like MP3 and OGG) for audio?": "<source>",
      "What is the purpose of the <track> tag?": "To provide subtitles or captions",
      "Which table tag is used to wrap the summary or totals at the bottom?": "<tfoot>",
      "What attribute allows an <iframe> to take up the full width of a container?": "width='100%'",
      "The Nevada Privacy Act SB220 uses which model for data sales?": "Opt-Out",
      "Which of the 'POUR' principles ensures a site can be used with a keyboard?": "Operable",
      "What is 'Dithering'?": "Simulating colors using patterns",
      "Why is JPG preferred over PNG for large, complex photographs?": "It has a much smaller file size due to lossy compression.",
      "What is the 'poster' attribute used for in a <video> tag?": "It specifies a static image to show before the video plays.",
      "Which image format was created by Google to provide superior lossless and lossy compression on the web?": "WebP",
      "Why is it considered a bad practice to use HTML tables for an entire page layout?": "They are not accessible to screen readers and break responsive design.",
      "What does the 'colspan' attribute do in a table data cell (<td>)?": "Stretches the cell horizontally across multiple columns.",
      "What does the 'rowspan' attribute do in a table cell?": "Stretches the cell vertically across multiple rows.",
      "If an image fails to load, which attribute's text will the browser display instead?": "alt",
      "Which HTML tag is semantically correct for defining the header row containing column titles in a table?": "<th>",
      "Why is embedding a YouTube video via <iframe> often better than hosting the MP4 yourself?": "You don't have to pay for the massive bandwidth the video uses.",
      "In the context of the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), what does 'Level AA' represent?": "The standard, legally targeted level of compliance.",
      "What happens during 'Lossy' compression (like saving a JPG)?": "Mathematical data is permanently deleted to reduce file size.",
      "What happens during 'Lossless' compression (like saving a PNG)?": "The file size is reduced by rewriting the data without losing visual quality.",
      "A site with light gray text on a white background fails which accessibility check?": "Color Contrast",
      "Which of the following is an example of an 'empty' or 'self-closing' HTML tag?": "<img>",
      "What does the <caption> tag do when used inside a <table>?": "It acts as a title or explanation specifically for that table.",
      "If you want an HTML5 video to automatically loop forever, which attribute do you add?": "loop",
      "What is the primary function of a Content Delivery Network (CDN)?": "To host copies of your media on servers globally to reduce load times for users far away.",
      "Which type of data is a SQL (Relational) database best suited for?": "Highly structured, interconnected data like bank accounts and user profiles.",
      "Which type of database stores data as flexible 'documents' rather than rigid tables?": "NoSQL (like MongoDB)",
      "If a user clears their browser cache, what happens to data saved in Local Storage?": "It is deleted entirely.",
      "In a relational database, what prevents two users from having the exact same identity record?": "The Primary Key",
      "The SQL command used to retrieve information from a database is:": "SELECT",
